Incorporating abuse (or anything else with actual resonance in real life) into an SCP or any ind of fantastic fiction is a very delicate thing that can easily go wrongkind of manages to work, by looking at the lasting psychological effects of such experiences instead of trying to be shocking. It's pretty good, actually.

Bonus points for having the SCP be the ritual (always nice to see more abstract takes on what an SCP can be) and the description mostly anchored to a presumably non-anomalous person who's just been snared by some vague but vaguely menacing thing. It manages to be both more abstract and more grounded than most.







